{{nihongo|'''''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation'''''|デビルサバイバーツー ジ・アニメーション|Debiru Sabaibā Tsū Ji Animēshon|lead=yes}} is a 2013 Japanese [[anime]] series based on the [[Nintendo DS]] video game, ''[[Shin Megami Tensei: Devil Survivor 2]]'' by [[Atlus]]. The series was directed by [[Seiji Kishi]], with series composition by [[Makoto Uezu]], based on the original story by Atlus and animated by [[Bridge (studio)|Bridge]]. The series stars voice actors [[Hiroshi Kamiya]] as Hibiki Kuze along with [[Nobuhiko Okamoto]], [[Aya Uchida]], [[Junichi Suwabe]] and [[Takahiro Sakurai]]. When a mysterious calamity plunges the world into a state of chaos, Hibiki Kuze and his friends Daichi Shijima and Io Nitta are suddenly thrown from their normal lives into a battle of survival against creatures called Septentriones seeking to bring the world to ruin. Gaining the ability to summon [[demons]] from a [[Mobile app|cell phone app]], Hibiki and his friends team up with an organization known as the JP's to help protect Japan and above all else—survive.

The thirteen episode series premiered in Japan on [[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]] on April 4, 2013 and was subsequently licensed by [[Section23 Films#Sentai Filmworks|Sentai Filmworks]] in North America, Hanabee Entertainment in Australia and New Zealand and by [[MVM Entertainment]] in the United Kingdom for English home video releases. A manga adaptation was serialized in ''[[Gangan Comics#Monthly GFantasy|Monthly GFantasy]]'' between December 2012 and October 2014. A light novel prequel was also published by [[Kodansha Box]]. In addition, two supplementary books and three Drama CDs along with a host of other merchandise were released. Critics praised the series for its dark animation styles and backgrounds. However the majority of reviewers had mixed feelings towards the cast of characters since they felt that while the characters were either not appealing or developed enough, their deaths were impactful to the viewer.

==Plot==
One Sunday afternoon, Hibiki Kuze and Daichi Shijima receive macabre videos from the {{Nihongo foot|Nicaea|ニカイア|Nikaia|group=J}} website which predict their deaths mere seconds before they are involved in a gruesome train accident. They are spared however, when a {{nihongo foot|Demon Summoning App|悪魔召喚アプリ|Akuma Shōkan Apuri|group=J}} installs itself on their phones and allows the duo and schoolmate Io Nitta to escape from carnivorous monsters feasting on the dead in the wrecked subway station. The trio are shocked to discover a massive catastrophe on the surface and take refuge in Roppongi with other panicked citizens. Suddenly, when a creature known as {{Nihongo4|Dubhe|ドゥベ|Duube}} appears and attacks the crowd, Hibiki puts a stop to the carnage by summoning a demon from the app and destroying the creature. This prompts the {{nihongo foot|Japan Meteorological Agency, Geomagnetism Research Department - JP's|気象庁・指定地磁気調査部、「ジプス」|Kishōchō. Shitei Chijiki Chōsa bu, 'Jipusu'|group=J}} to detain Hibiki and his friends and they are brought before its head—Yamato Hotsuin, who enlists their aid in defeating the remaining {{nihongo foot|Septentriones|セプテントリオン|Seputentorion|group=J}} to prevent the end of the world in one week.

Yamato then dispatches them on a mission to retrieve the JP's scientist Fumi Kanno with fellow demon summoners Hinako Kujou and Keita Wakui, which ends up as a success at the cost of Keita's life. Following a devastating battle with {{Nihongo4|Merak|メラク|Meraku}}, Hibiki joins the Resistance leader—Ronaldo Kuriki and learns of [[meritocracy|Yamato's true intentions]] as opposed to [[Egalitarianism|his own]]. As events progress, Airi Ban and Jungo Torii attempt to recapture the JP's base from the Resistance but chaos ensues when {{Nihongo4|Phecda|フェクダ|Fekuda}} appears and targets a defenseless Hibiki. However Yamato arrives and slays the Septentrione, saving Hibiki's life. In the aftermath, Yamato and Ronaldo engage in a heated debate over their ideals and the situation only escalates when Alcor appears and proclaims himself to be the creator of both Nicaea and the Demon Summoning App, which he had hoped would aid humanity in their darkest hour.

An unlikely alliance between the JP's, Resistance and the unaffiliated demon summoners result in the destruction of {{Nihongo4|Megrez|メグレズ|Megurezu}} the following day. While a somber Hibiki struggles to cope with the steep cost of victory, Alcor reveals the true nature of events thus far. He explains it all to be the will of an entity known as {{Nihongo4|Polaris|ポラリス|Porarisu}} as it seeks to erase humanity's "artificial" reality using its Void phenomenon and hence restore the "natural" order. Therefore, it sent the Septentriones to destroy the spiritual barriers protecting Japan from the Void. When Hinako and Airi defeat {{Nihongo4|Alioth|アリオト|Arioto}} the next day, its massive shell plummets from orbit and crushes the city—killing thousands more people and sparking outrage from Hibiki over the lengths Yamato will go to achieve his goal. Unperturbed, Yamato uses Io to summon a demon called Lugh and defeats the next Septentrione—{{Nihongo4|Mizar|ミザール|Mizaaru}}. However, when the demon possesses Io and attempts to kill Yamato for its imprisonment, Hibiki wields the {{Nihongo foot|Dragon Stream|龍脈|Ryumyaku|group=J}} and saves Io.

As the week draws to a close, {{Nihongo4|Benetnasch|ベネトナシュ|Benetonashu}} appears on Saturday and completely destroys the barriers. Upon engaging the creature, Yamato allows the other summoners to die by ignoring them in the battle and ultimately defeats it with Hibiki and Daichi's help. In the aftermath, Alcor decides to support Hibiki and Yamato ends up killing him. Finally, Yamato activates the Transport Terminal to seek an audience with Polaris and Io and Daichi forfeit their lives to give Hibiki a chance at going after Yamato and saving the world. Facing each other in another dimension, Hibiki desperately tries to reach out to Yamato and ultimately overpowers him with aid from his fallen comrades. Polaris then appears and Hibiki asks it to restore the world to the way it was. He then finds himself one week in the past, with his revived friends and his memory intact and reifies the will of humanity to keep on living.

===Main characters===
;{{Nihongo4|Hibiki Kuze|久世 響希|Kuze Hibiki}}
:{{animevoices|[[Hiroshi Kamiya]]<ref name="DS2A Staff"/>|Patrick Poole<ref name="English Cast">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-06-04/sentai-filmworks-announces-full-devil-survivor-2-dub-cast/.74929|title=Sentai Filmworks Announces Full ''Devil Survivor 2'' Dub Cast|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|accessdate=June 6, 2014|date=June 4, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140605202236/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-06-04/sentai-filmworks-announces-full-devil-survivor-2-dub-cast/.74929|archivedate=June 5, 2014|df=}}</ref>}}
:Hibiki is the 18-year-old protagonist of the series. He is granted the ability to summon demons from Nicaea after experiencing a train accident on his way home from taking mock exams. With this newfound power he finds himself intertwined in a battle of survival against the Septentriones who seek to destroy the world.<ref name="Hibiki">{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/character/#hibiki_kuze|title=Character｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 9, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927021016/http://ds2a.jp/character/#hibiki_kuze|archivedate=September 27, 2013|df=}}</ref> Kamiya did not express any opinions on Hibiki's character. However he was very clear to point out that despite the series being called ''Devil Survivor 2'', it is not a sequel to a previous series but rather an independent story all its own.<ref name="Cast Interview 1">{{cite web|url=http://blog.ds2a.jp/archives/100|title=メインキャスト陣が語るTVアニメ『DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION』 TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」NEWS|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 9, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140109073408/http://blog.ds2a.jp/archives/100|archivedate=January 9, 2014|df=}}</ref>

;{{Nihongo4|Daichi Shijima|志島 大地|Shijima Daichi}}
:{{animevoices|[[Nobuhiko Okamoto]]<ref name="DS2A Staff"/>|[[Greg Ayres]]<ref name="English Cast"/>}}
:Daichi is Hibiki's best friend and was with him during the train accident where he was also granted the power of summoning demons from Nicaea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/character/#daichi_shijima|title=Character｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 9, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927021016/http://ds2a.jp/character/#daichi_shijima|archivedate=September 27, 2013|df=}}</ref> Okamoto praised the visual effects of the nighttime battle scenes, describing them as being "very beautiful".<ref name="Cast Interview 1"/>

;{{Nihongo4|Io Nitta|新田 維緒|Nitta Io}}
:{{animevoices|[[Aya Uchida]]<ref name="DS2A Staff"/>|[[Jessica Boone]]<ref name="English Cast"/>}}
:Io is a beautiful and intelligent senior at the same high school attended by Hibiki and Daichi. She was also granted the power of demon summoning by Nicaea after being involved in the train accident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/character/#io_nitta|title=Character｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 9, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927021016/http://ds2a.jp/character/#io_nitta|archivedate=September 27, 2013|df=}}</ref> Uchida remarked that players of the original ''Devil Survivor 2'' video game would enjoy the various viewpoints presented in the series. She also felt that the audience would be able to empathize with the characters since they are portrayed in a way that begs the question, "What would you do in that situation?"<ref name="Cast Interview 1"/>

;{{Nihongo4|Yamato Hotsuin|峰津院 大和|Hotsuin Yamato}}
:{{animevoices|[[Junichi Suwabe]]<ref name="DS2A Staff"/>|[[John Gremillion]]<ref name="English Cast"/>}}
:Yamato is the director of the Japan Meteorological Agency, Geomagnetism Research Department which was established by his own Hotsuin family. He is a level-headed thinker and able to maintain composure in most situations.<ref name="Yamato">{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/character/#yamato_hotsuin|title=Character｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 9, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927021016/http://ds2a.jp/character/#yamato_hotsuin|archivedate=September 27, 2013|df=}}</ref> Suwabe praised the cohesiveness of the music, video and dialogue of the series. He also noted that Yamato's most appealing trait is his strength.<ref name="Cast Interview 1"/>

;{{Nihongo4|Anguished One|憂う者|Ureumono}} / {{Nihongo4|"Alcor"||}}
:{{animevoices|[[Takahiro Sakurai]]<ref name="DS2A Staff"/>|[[Illich Guardiola]]<ref name="English Cast"/>}}
:A mysterious white-haired individual who appears to Hibiki and Yamato at various times during the week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/character/#anguished_one|title=Character｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 9, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927021016/http://ds2a.jp/character/#anguished_one|archivedate=September 27, 2013|df=}}</ref> He is the creator of the Nicaea website and the Demon Summoning App.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Wednesday of Transformations I|series=''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation''|credits=Makoto Uezu|network=[[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]]|airdate=May 16, 2013|time=06:31|quote='''Alcor''': So I made Nicaea and gave you these tools...}}</ref> Also known as "Alcor", he is the 8th Septentrione.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Wednesday of Transformations II|series=''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation''|credits=Makoto Uezu|network=[[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]]|airdate=May 23, 2013|time=18:48|quote='''Alcor''': I'm one of the Septentriones.}}</ref> Sakurai described Alcor's enigmatic appeal as laying in the aspect of being part of something larger than himself. He went on to praise the animation style, describing it as "powerful and immersive".<ref name="Cast Interview 1"/>

==Production==
[[File:SH-60B helicopter flies over Sendai.jpg|thumb|Director Seiji Kishi compared the destruction depicted in the anime to the [[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami]] which struck Japan.]]
''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation'' was produced by the [[Bridge (studio)|Bridge]] animation studio of Japan using a team henceforth known as the ''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation'' Committee.<ref name="DS2A Staff">{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/cast-staff/|title=Cast & Staff｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 25, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927041812/http://ds2a.jp/cast-staff/|archivedate=September 27, 2013|df=}}</ref> The series was directed by veteran anime director [[Seiji Kishi]] best known for directing the anime adaptation of Atlus's 2008 video game ''[[Persona 4]]''.<ref name="Director Kishi / Manga">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-12-07/persona-4-kishi-directs-devil-survivor-2-game-tv-anime|title=''Persona 4'''s Kishi Directs ''Devil Survivor 2'' RPG's TV Anime|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 7, 2012|accessdate=August 25, 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414222602/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-12-07/persona-4-kishi-directs-devil-survivor-2-game-tv-anime|archivedate=April 14, 2016|df=}}</ref> During production, Kishi remarked that the calamity of which the story describes was reminiscent of the [[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami]].<ref name="DS2A Staff Comments 01">{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/special/comment01.html/|title=Special｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 25, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815212729/http://ds2a.jp/special/comment01.html|archivedate=August 15, 2013|df=}}</ref> He also praised the animated depictions of Suzuhito Yasuda's character designs. [[Makoto Uezu]] was selected as both the script writer and series composer for the anime. In an interview, Uezu commented that he had been a huge fan of the ''[[Megami Tensei]]'' series since his childhood and that his interests in the [[occult]] and electronic technology aided in the composition. Uezu further remarked that the story followed a "hard path" whereby the heroes were forced into making difficult choices at key points in the plot whilst the characters simultaneously explored sensitive issues related to human ethics and morality.<ref name="DS2A Staff Comments 01"/>

The series' character designs were drawn by Etsushi Sajima and were based on the original designs by Suzuhito Yasuda which received praise from Director Kishi.<ref name="DS2A Staff Comments 01"/> The original designs of the Septentriones were created by Mohiro Kitoh who remarked that since he was not directly engaged in the production process, he had to wait until the finished product was released before he could see the animated versions of his designs.<ref name="DS2A Staff Comments 02">{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/special/comment02.html|title=Special｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 25, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815140805/http://ds2a.jp/special/comment02.html|archivedate=August 15, 2013|df=}}</ref> The other half of the series' creatures i.e. the various ''devils'' (demons) used were designed by Hiroyuki Kanbe, while prop designs were done by Hatsue Nakayama and color designs were done by Keiichi Funada. Finally leaving Kazuto Shimoyama to oversee this area of production as the art director. The musical score was composed by [[Kōtarō Nakagawa]]. Nakagawa was initially surprised to have been offered to be the musical composer but took up the role as a challenge.<ref name="DS2A Staff Comments 02"/> In addition to Nagakawa, Sound Direction was done by Satoki Iida along with Sound Effects by Iki Okuda. Other staff members included Assistant Director Yoshimichi Hirai, Animation Designer Eriko Ito, Composite Director Katsufumi Sato, CG Director Yuji Koshida and Ayumu Takahashi as the series Editor and Producer Yasuo Suda.<ref name="DS2A Staff"/>

===Music and audio===

''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation'' uses three pieces of [[theme music]]: one opening theme, one closing theme and one insert song. The theme sequences are not used consistently throughout the series since the episode producers decided to prioritize story-telling to their use which helped keep the plot within thirteen episodes.<ref name="Silverman Review 01"/> The anime debuted with "Take Your Way" by [[Livetune]] feat. [[Sekai no Owari|Fukase]] as the opening theme for the first eight episodes and then from the eleventh.<ref name="Op/Ed">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-03-27/devil-survivor-2-anime-theme-songs-previewed-in-2-more-ads|title=''Devil Survivor 2'' Anime's Theme Songs Previewed in 2 More Ads|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 27, 2013|accessdate=September 7, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140913175411/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-03-27/devil-survivor-2-anime-theme-songs-previewed-in-2-more-ads|archivedate=September 13, 2014|df=}}</ref> The theme is not played but credited in both the ninth<ref>{{cite episode|title=Thursday of Shock|series=''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation''|credits=Makoto Uezu|network=[[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]]|airdate=May 30, 2013|time=02:11}}</ref> and tenth<ref>{{cite episode|title=Friday of Farewells|series=''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation''|credits=Makoto Uezu|network=[[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]]|airdate=June 6, 2013|time=03:43}}</ref> episodes. The closing theme is "Be" by [[:ja:Song Riders|Song Riders]] and is used from the first through ninth episodes and then from the eleventh.<ref name="Op/Ed"/> The insert song titled "Each and All" by Livetune feat. [[:ja:Q;indivi|Rin Oikawa]] also doubled as the closing theme of the tenth episode.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Friday of Farewells|series=''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation''|credits=Makoto Uezu|network=[[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]]|airdate=June 6, 2013|time=19:08}}</ref>

Song Riders released "Be" on May 22, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ds2a.jp/products/edtheme.html|title=Products :「TRAUMA / Be」｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 26, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815144051/http://ds2a.jp/products/edtheme.html|archivedate=August 15, 2013|df=}}</ref> This was followed by the release of Livetune's "Take Your Way" single on June 5, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ds2a.jp/products/optheme.html|title=Products :「Take Your Way」｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 26, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815223257/http://ds2a.jp/products/optheme.html|archivedate=August 15, 2013|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://livetune.jp/discography/702|title=livetune adding Fukase（from SEKAI NO OWARI）  『Take Your Way』|publisher=[[Livetune]] Official Website|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 26, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131226171110/http://livetune.jp/discography/702|archivedate=December 26, 2013|df=}}</ref> "Take Your Way" sold 9,776 copies in its first week, ranking number 12 on the [[Oricon Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/w/2013-06-17/more/3/|title=CDシングル 週間ランキング-音楽ランキング|publisher=[[Oricon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=January 10, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130612070404/http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/w/2013-06-17/more/3/|archivedate=June 12, 2013|df=}}</ref> The song went on to become the number 1 single for the 23rd week of 2013.<ref name="CR livetune">{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2013/06/13/tower-records-shinjuku-weekly-anime-song-top-10-june-3-9|title=TOWER RECORDS Shinjuku Weekly Anime Song TOP 10 June 3–9|publisher=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=June 14, 2013|accessdate=January 10, 2014|first=Mikikazu|last=Komatsu|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618010856/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2013/06/13/tower-records-shinjuku-weekly-anime-song-top-10-june-3-9|archivedate=June 18, 2013|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mantan-web.jp/2013/06/13/20130613dog00m200037000c.html|title=新宿アニソンスコープ：アニメ「デビルサバイバー2」OPが1位　RAYアルバムも健闘 - MANTANWEB（まんたんウェブ）|publisher=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|language=Japanese|date=June 13, 2013|accessdate=January 10, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823065731/http://mantan-web.jp/2013/06/13/20130613dog00m200037000c.html|archivedate=August 23, 2013|df=}}</ref> The official "Take Your Way" music video features visuals and direction by Fantasia Utomaro.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2013/05/04/video-animated-teaser-for-take-your-way-by-livetune|title=VIDEO: Animated Teaser for "Take Your Way" by livetune|publisher=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=June 14, 2013|accessdate=January 10, 2014|first=Patrick|last=Macias|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507115710/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2013/05/04/video-animated-teaser-for-take-your-way-by-livetune|archivedate=May 7, 2013|df=}}</ref> The first soundtrack album was bundled with the first Blu-ray and DVD volume of the series and released in Japan on June 19, 2013.<ref name="BD Volume 1"/> The second album was released in a similar manner, with the third Blu-ray and DVD volume and released on August 21, 2013.<ref name="BD Volume 3">{{cite web|url=http://ds2a.jp/products/bd_01.html#vol3|title=Products :Blu-ray&DVD Vol.3｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 26, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817181541/http://ds2a.jp/products/bd_01.html#vol3|archivedate=August 17, 2013|df=}}</ref>

A bi-weekly internet radio show hosted by Shūta Morishima was broadcast between April 4 and July 11, 2013 on the [[:jp:HiBiKi Radio Station|Hibiki Radio]] and [[:jp:音泉|Sound Springs]] stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presepe.jp/anime_news/radio_programs/tvアニメ「デビルサバイバー２」ラジオ配信決定|title=TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー２」ラジオ配信決定 アニメニュース｜アニメ情報とショップ＆コミュニティ -プレセペ-|publisher=Presepe|language=Japanese|date=March 28, 2013|accessdate=January 9, 2014}}</ref> Three drama CDs were additionally released and bundled with the second, fourth and seventh Blu-ray and DVD volumes on July 17, 2013,<ref name="DCD1">{{cite web|url=http://ds2a.jp/products/bd_01.html#vol2|title=Products :Blu-ray&DVD Vol.2｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 26, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817181541/http://ds2a.jp/products/bd_01.html#vol2|archivedate=August 17, 2013|df=}}</ref> September 19, 2013<ref name="DCD2">{{cite web|url=http://ds2a.jp/products/bd_01.html#vol4|title=Products :Blu-ray&DVD Vol.4｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 26, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817181541/http://ds2a.jp/products/bd_01.html#vol4|archivedate=August 17, 2013|df=}}</ref> and December 18, 2013<ref name="DCD3">{{cite web|url=http://ds2a.jp/products/bd_01.html#vol7|title=Products :Blu-ray&DVD Vol.7｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=November 22, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130817181541/http://ds2a.jp/products/bd_01.html#vol7|archivedate=August 17, 2013|df=}}</ref> respectively. The CDs collectively tell parts of a story titled, {{nihongo foot|"Ganbare Hibiki-kun!"|がんばれヒビキくん！||group=J}}.

