===Light novels===
A light novel written by Katsumi Amagawa titled "Devil Survivor 2 The Animation: Cetus's Prequel" was published by [[Kodansha Box]] on June 3, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bookclub.kodansha.co.jp/bc2_bc/search_view.jsp?b=2838486|script-title=ja:ＤＥＶＩＬ　ＳＵＲＶＩＶＯＲ２　ＴＨＥ　ＡＮＩＭＡＴＩＯＮ　公式ノベライズ　くじら座のプリクエル 新沢克海 講談社|publisher=[[Kodansha Box]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 26, 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429183316/http://bookclub.kodansha.co.jp/bc2_bc/search_view.jsp?b=2838486|archivedate=April 29, 2014|df=}}</ref> The events of the novel take place before the anime and depict a younger Yamato as Director of JP's and his preparation for the coming apocalypse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/products/novel_01.html|title=Products :ノベライズ「くじら座のプリクエル」｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 24, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815140754/http://ds2a.jp/products/novel_01.html|archivedate=August 15, 2013|df=}}</ref> A supplementary book titled "Devil Survivor 2 The Animation: Character Archives" was published by Square Enix on June 27, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jp.square-enix.com/magazine/top/introduction/detail/9784757539983.html|title=DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION CHARACTER ARCHIVES 公式サイト: ATLUS: スクウェア・エニックス: ファンブック: スクウェア・エニックス|publisher=[[Square Enix]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=July 22, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707040512/http://www.jp.square-enix.com/magazine/top/introduction/detail/9784757539983.html|archivedate=July 7, 2013|df=}}</ref> The book contained character biographies in addition to commentaries by Seiji Kishi and Makoto Uezu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/products/characterarchives.html|title=Products :キャラクターアーカイヴス｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=September 15, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815143257/http://ds2a.jp/products/characterarchives.html|archivedate=August 15, 2013|df=}}</ref> Another book titled "Devil Survivor 2 The Animation: Creator Works" was published by Pony Canyon in Japan on August 9, 2013. This book contained broad interviews from most of the animation staff, including photos and a behind-the-scene look at the animation process and at the ''Devil Survivor 2'' world.<ref name="Creator Works">{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/products/creatorworks.html|title=Products :クリエイターワークス｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=September 15, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807083411/http://ds2a.jp/products/creatorworks.html|archivedate=August 7, 2013|df=}}</ref>

===Merchandising===
Numerous products including figurines and mobile phone accessories among other things were released in response to the anime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ds2a.jp/products/etc.html|title=Products：その他グッズ｜TVアニメ「デビルサバイバー2」公式サイト［DEVIL SURVIVOR2 the ANIMATION］|publisher=[[Pony Canyon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=September 15, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815095939/http://ds2a.jp/products/etc.html|archivedate=August 15, 2013|df=}}</ref> A set of 16 posters was released by ''Pos x Pos Collection'' on October 18, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2013/07/30-1/devil-survivor-2-anime-poster-collection-up-for-pre-order|title="''Devil Survivor 2''" Anime Poster Collection Up For Pre-Order|publisher=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=July 30, 2013|accessdate=January 9, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824015709/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2013/07/30-1/devil-survivor-2-anime-poster-collection-up-for-pre-order|archivedate=August 24, 2013|df=}}</ref>

==Reception==
The first episode earned an audience approval rating of 1.4% in Osaka's [[Kansai region|Kansai]] area and 1.9% in Tokyo's [[Kantō region|Kantō]] area during its premiere on April 4 and 5 in those regions respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-04-09/devil-survivor-2-earns-1.4-percent-and-1.9-percent-ratings-in-late-night|title=''Devil Survivor 2'' Earns 1.4% & 1.9% Ratings in Late-Night|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 9, 2013|accessdate=August 20, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922005528/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-04-09/devil-survivor-2-earns-1.4-percent-and-1.9-percent-ratings-in-late-night|archivedate=September 22, 2014|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2022677/full|script-title=ja:深夜アニメ『デビサバ2』好スタート |publisher=[[Oricon]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref> The first Japanese DVD volume of the series sold 1,933 copies in its first week, ranking number 7 on the [[Oricon]] DVD Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-06-25/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-june-17-23|title=Japan's Animation DVD Ranking, June 17–23|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 6, 2013|accessdate=August 20, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140815104503/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-06-25/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-june-17-23|archivedate=August 15, 2014|df=}}</ref> Its second volume ranked 12, selling 844 copies in its first week,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-07-23/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-july-15-21|title=Japan's Animation DVD Ranking, July 15–21|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 23, 2013|accessdate=September 15, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140827115128/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-07-23/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-july-15-21|archivedate=August 27, 2014|df=}}</ref> while its third debuted at number 23 with 721 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-08-27/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-august-19-25|title=Japan's Animation DVD Ranking, August 19–25|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 27, 2013|accessdate=September 15, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814190422/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-08-27/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-august-19-25|archivedate=August 14, 2014|df=}}</ref> Its sixth volume ranked at number 13 and sold 648 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-11-26/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-november-18-24|title=Japan's Animation DVD Ranking, November 18–24|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 26, 2013|accessdate=September 15, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141005054131/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-11-26/japan-animation-dvd-ranking-november-18-24|archivedate=October 5, 2014|df=}}</ref> The second Japanese Blu-ray volume of the series sold 1,488 copies in its first week, ranking number 9 on the Oricon Blu-ray Chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-07-23/japan-animation-blu-ray-disc-ranking-july-15-21|title=Japan's Animation Blu-ray Disc Ranking, July 15–21|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 23, 2013|accessdate=September 15, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140918060456/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-07-23/japan-animation-blu-ray-disc-ranking-july-15-21|archivedate=September 18, 2014|df=}}</ref> while the sixth volume debuted at number 10 and sold 1,200 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-11-26/japan-animation-blu-ray-disc-ranking-november-18-24|title=Japan's Animation Blu-ray Disc Ranking, November 18–24|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 26, 2013|accessdate=September 15, 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140925065046/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2013-11-26/japan-animation-blu-ray-disc-ranking-november-18-24|archivedate=September 25, 2014|df=}}</ref>

A seasonal review column on the [[Anime News Network]] called ''The Stream'' generally made light remarks of the first four episodes. Written by Bamboo Dong, the editor called the series mindlessly fun; jokingly citing how the cell phones are always pointed directly at the demons as if they would be incapable of fighting if it were otherwise. Dong also likened the series as watching someone else play the video game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-stream/2013-05-06#ds2|title=#11 - ''Devil Survivor 2 The Animation'' [ep. 1-4]|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=May 6, 2013|accessdate=April 24, 2015|first=Bamboo|last=Dong|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309024236/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-stream/2013-05-06#ds2|archivedate=March 9, 2015|df=}}</ref> The designs of the various demons and Septentriones were described as the most interesting part of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-stream/2013-06-03#ds2|title=#14 - ''Devil Survivor 2 The Animation'' [ep. 5-8]|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 3, 2013|accessdate=April 24, 2015|first=Bamboo|last=Dong|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405024311/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-stream/2013-06-03#ds2|archivedate=April 5, 2015|df=}}</ref> On the other hand, the editor described the immense amount of [video game] plot packed into the next batch of four episodes as messy. Dong also referred to the central premise as being pretty dark since it involved the main characters constantly receiving videos showing exactly how their friends would die. The editor gave the series props for not dabbling in the destruction porn taking place since all of the widespread death around Japan is implied, but added that showing some of it would have aided the realism of the story. After reviewing twelve episodes Dong was not able to develop any interest in the characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-stream/2013-06-24#ds2|title=#10 - ''Devil Survivor 2 The Animation'' [ep. 9-12]|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 24, 2013|accessdate=April 24, 2015|first=Bamboo|last=Dong|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418055358/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-stream/2013-06-24#ds2|archivedate=April 18, 2015|df=}}</ref> This continued into the series finale and Dong still felt that the characters were not fleshed out as much as they could have been. Dong explained that since there was basically no time to explore how the characters reacted to a ''disappearing world'', it was essentially dehumanizing to such an extent that their deaths carried no emotional weight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-stream/2013-07-15#ds2|title=#12 - ''Devil Survivor 2 The Animation'' [ep. 13]|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 15, 2013|accessdate=April 24, 2015|first=Bamboo|last=Dong|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711021924/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-stream/2013-07-15#ds2|archivedate=July 11, 2015|df=}}</ref> Dong presented a full series review in their ''Shelf Life'' column and expressed that viewers who like brawn, action and some emotion will enjoy the series as long as they can come to terms with the fact that they'll pretty much just be watching someone play a video game for several hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/shelf-life/2014-06-30/.76151#ds2|title=Rental Shelf ''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation'' BD|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 30, 2014|accessdate=April 24, 2015|first=Bamboo|last=Dong|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424134442/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/shelf-life/2014-06-30/.76151#ds2|archivedate=April 24, 2015|df=}}</ref>

[[File:Kanto-daishinsai.jpg|right|thumb|The destruction caused in the series was thought of as being similar to the real-world devastation brought to Japan by the [[1923 Great Kantō earthquake]].]]
''The Spring 2013 Anime Preview Guide'' written by Rebecca Silverman, also of the Anime News Network, expressed differing sentiments than that of Dong. Silverman was quick to mention that she had not previously played the game to which the series was based on. With that being said, she described the first episode as not feeling like a game adaptation since you at no point have the sensation of watching someone else play. She also noted that the transformation from the everyday world to one of total chaos and destruction as both swift and impressive. She supported this by citing similar descriptions of the destruction caused by the [[1923 Great Kantō earthquake|Great Kantō earthquake]] of the 1920s.<ref name="Silverman Review 00">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/preview-guide/2013/the-spring-anime/rebecca|title=The Spring 2013 Anime Preview Guide / ''Devil Survivor 2 The Animation''|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 3, 2013|accessdate=November 22, 2013|first=Rebecca|last=Silverman|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407042606/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/preview-guide/2013/the-spring-anime/rebecca|archivedate=April 7, 2013|df=}}</ref> In her full series review, Silverman went into detail about how noticeably dark the series as a whole is when taking into account its animated depictions coupled with the death themes used. Unlike fellow reviewer Bamboo Dong, Silverman felt that character deaths would hit viewers more personally since they get to know them as the story progress and are then suddenly torn down. She further wrote that nearly every character death can potentially pack a punch since they are removed from the ending animation upon their demise. On the other hand, Silverman remarked that some of the characters were truly unlikable as they did not appear to grow and change.<ref name="Silverman Review 01">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/devil-survivor-2-the-animation|title=Review: ''Devil Survivor 2 The Animation'' by Rebecca Silverman|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 18, 2013|accessdate=September 8, 2013|first=Rebecca|last=Silverman|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130825031135/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/review/devil-survivor-2-the-animation|archivedate=August 25, 2013|df=}}</ref>

After seven episodes, Richard Eisenbeis of [[Kotaku]] disliked the series so much that he discouraged viewers from watching it for that particular season. He supported this by stating that the premise of teenagers summoning monsters has been done to death and that the adaptation has no compelling mysteries nor are there deeper psychological dilemmas being explored.<ref name="Eisenbeis Review 00">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/four-anime-you-can-skip-this-season-507970495|title=Four Anime You Can Skip This Season|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|date=May 17, 2013|accessdate=November 26, 2013|first=Richard|last=Eisenbeis|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131122063852/http://kotaku.com/four-anime-you-can-skip-this-season-507970495|archivedate=November 22, 2013|df=}}</ref> Eisenbeis shared sentiments with the Anime News Network reviewers when he elaborated on what he called the "woefully underdeveloped" characters of ''Devil Survivor 2'' who are only given rudimentary back-stories. This had the added effect of making it nearly impossible to figure out who exactly is a one-off character and who is a main character since they are all equally subjected to the threat of death. Eisenbeis noted that this made their demise genuinely shocking as it added to the viewing tension. Eisenbeis went on to write that the other characters were contrast to the main villain (or [[antihero]]) Yamato Hotsuin since he gets so much development that much of the series' runtime is spent on his backstory and goals than all the other characters combined. This helps give an in-depth understanding of the character and simultaneously made him an excellent villain.<ref name="Eisenbeis Review">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/devil-survivor-2-is-much-better-than-i-expected-958700348|title=''Devil Survivor 2'' Is Much Better Than I Expected|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|date=July 30, 2013|accessdate=September 8, 2013|first=Richard|last=Eisenbeis|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906060219/http://kotaku.com/devil-survivor-2-is-much-better-than-i-expected-958700348|archivedate=September 6, 2013|df=}}</ref>

The UK Anime Network had Andy Hanley review the first four episodes and he expressed a much more positive outlook than previous reviewers. Hanley wrote about how fast the series was in setting up its premise and described it as an ''in at the deep end'' experience. Hanley cited the ruination of Tokyo at the end of the first episode and the countless deaths that occur by episode four to support this. Hanley argued that while this pace leaves the series open to being labelled as shallow, it's actually very effective in keeping the viewer engaged.<ref name="Hanley Review">{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-anime.net/anime/Devil_Survivor_2:_The_Animation_-_Eps._1-4.html|title=ANIME REVIEW: ''Devil Survivor 2: The Animation'' - Eps. 1-4|publisher=UK Anime Network|date=|accessdate=July 22, 2014|first=Andy|last=Hanley|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403234942/http://uk-anime.net/anime/Devil_Survivor_2:_The_Animation_-_Eps._1-4.html|archivedate=April 3, 2015|df=}}</ref>

