{{Unreferenced stub|date=November 2010}}

In [[classical drama]], the '''epitasis''' ({{lang-grc|ἐπίτασις}}) is the main action of a play, in which the trials and tribulations of the main character increase and build toward a climax and dénouement. It is the third and central part when a play is analyzed into five separate parts: prelude, [[protasis]], epitasis, [[catastasis]] and [[Catastrophe (drama)|catastrophe]].

In modern [[dramatic theory]], the [[Dramatic structure|dramatic arc]] is often referred to, which uses somewhat different divisions but is substantially the same concept overall.{{fact|date=April 2013}}

[[Category:Drama]]
[[Category:Ancient Greek theatre]]

{{Lit-stub}}

{{Orphan|date=October 2010}}
'''Illyrian amber figures''' are a group of small human and animal figures made out of amber. They were made from the start of the [[Iron Age]] around [[1000BC]] and their production continued down through the millennium. They  are found in nearly all of [[Illyria]] from [[Slovenia]] in the north to [[Albania]] and [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] in the south. The sites with the most figures found are Ripac in [[Bosnia]] (15 figures in total of animals and humans) and Ormozh in Slovenia (10 human and 13 animal figures). The purpose of these figures is still a mystery and they could as well have been Illyrian deities, figures to represent the cult of the dead or simply children's toys. Amber was a plastic that Illyrians were very fond of and many of their jewellery and decorative objects were made of amber. For these figures it is hard to say that they are artistic objects.<ref>{{harvnb|Stipčević|1989}}.</ref>

